INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L157$$, 2027, $$Naval Criminal Investigative Service (NCIS) mission supports day-to-day operations to Prevent Terrorism, Protect National Secrets, Reduce Crime across the Department of the Navy (DON) and comply with
 DON Mandates. NCIS IT Programs and Technical Support are essential to fulfill its mission.

 Electronic Military Personnel Record System (EMPRS) is an electronic document/image based system that serves as the official repository for all Department of Navy (DON) official military personnel record
 images (over 170 million images). It supports active, reserve and retired/separated military personnel in the functional areas of selection board operations, casualty management, mobilization, veteran benefits
 (providing automated Sailor information to the Veterans Administration) and other military personnel management functions. EMPRS annually supports over 150 statutory and administrative selection boards,
 providing over 12 million service record images, covering promotions, assignments, and retention.

 PDAS Equipment Modernization: Planning and Decision Aid System (PDAS) is a classified, protected program operated by the Navy. PDAS is a command-and-control system that provides capabilities to Office
 of the Secretary of War, services, Unified Combatant Commanders (CCMD), Intelligence Community and Coalition partners for operational planning/coordination of special access programs (SAPs). PDAS
 enables Integrated Joint Special Technical operations (IJSTO) to incorporate SAPs into operational planning and execution from battlefield operators through the Commander-in-Chief in support of national
 security objectives. PDAS is the system for the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff (CJCS) for IJSTO.

 Maritime Operational Battlespace Command & Control (MOB C2) (formerly MOC) program of record supports Maritime Operation Centers by providing enhanced operational capabilities through delivery of
 Missile Defense applications through MOC Workstations (MWS). This includes hardware tech refresh, integration, testing, and installations that enable MOCs to effectively monitor the battlespace, Link-16
 tracks, and maintain space situation awareness. MOB C2 also provides Joint Integrated Voice-Video Enterprise Systems (JIVES), formerly Naval Video Services (NVS), which provides a standardized enterprise
 solution with a common baseline across all MOCs, adhering to MOC Core Baseline/Mission Build (CB/MB) requirements. MOB C2 is leading the Commander 7th Fleet (C7F) Move Ashore effort as well. This will
 guarantee the Fleet's continued full operational capacity for USS Blue Ridge dry-docking by establishing a secure and effective command and control shore location. MOB C2 also supports the "Fight From the
 MOC" initiative by tracking critical systems required for full Fleet interoperability. This initiative focuses on priority sites, including Commander Pacific Fleet (CPF), Commander 3rd Fleet (C3F), Commander 7th
 Fleet (C7F), and Commander 10th Fleet (C10F) by leveraging complex C4I systems to provide standardized interoperability. This program is crucial for maintaining missile defense readiness and INDOPACOM
 operational command and control capabilities, ensuring Fleet commanders can effectively coordinate defensive operations and maintain vital situational awareness across the Pacific theater's complex threat
 environment. Additionally, MOB C2 provides deployable Distributed Command, Control & Communications to provide real-time situational awareness and decision support across all domains.$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                      Date: April 2026
