INSERT INTO public.proc_line_narratives (proc_line_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, raw_text, source_pdf, source_page_description, source_page_amount, content_hash, ingested_at) VALUES ($$P_1810_L170$$, 2026, $$The Next Generation Enterprise Network (NGEN) program mission is to ensure and provide a modernized enterprise approach to delivery of a fully integrated, interoperable, and secure networking platform
 capable of delivering the information technology (IT)-based mission needs of major Fleet and shore-based Navy claimants and stakeholders. The network has begun modernization efforts towards a flexible
 and agile IT standard approach, using an architecture and service strategy aligned with commercial best practices. The new service delivery approach features diverse sourcing, leveraging of cloud/web-scale
 infrastructure and software-defined flexibility, which the Navy will seek to take advantage of the NGEN Re-compete (NGEN-R) family of contracts.

 NGEN is implementing a technical enterprise architecture that replaces obsolete technologies associated with Navy/Marine Corps Intranet (NMCI) and ONE-Net platforms. Navy's Digitization Journey is
 dependent upon the Navy's Enterprise Network. The modernized platform will meet today's and future mission requirements. Current on-premise infrastructure must transform and evolve to a future cloud native
 environment to enable the warfighter to access data across multiple domains. Through recapitalization of applicable legacy hardware and converging network infrastructure toward a cloud native design, NGEN
 will reduce the need for constant platform reconfiguration and ensure the end-user receives current capabilities required to perform job functions at various classification levels. Multifactor authentication and
 centralized management of user personas enables zero-trust based cyber security from the onset of system development throughout the entire lifecycle. Uniform enterprise security controls across the system
 lifecycle ensures consistency across the development, testing, and operational phased deployment workflow thus reducing rework. The flattened network design will enable contracting and acquisitions to quickly
 deploy solutions from the labs to the user community in near real-time.

 Key objectives of the compliance based technical refresh and modernization approach include the broad implementation of the following:

 Network Management: The Network Product Group requires compliance-based tech refresh of Continental United States (CONUS) and Outside the Continental United States (OCONUS) hardware/software
 required to support network performance and resiliency for the warfighter. A significant amount of these assets has reached end-of-life and are no longer supported by the vendors, leaving failed hardware
 without replacement options and opening the network to vulnerabilities with unsupported software which diminishes enterprise solutions, performance, and optimization. Our current infrastructure is aged, and
 refresh is essential to accommodate new emerging workforce requirements and maintain network performance and architecture/solution accreditations until capabilities can be transformed.

 Cybersecurity: Compliance-based tech refresh to pace the obsolescence-based cyber security threat until replaced by Network Transformation efforts. Upgrade of NMCI hardware/software and assigned non-
 IT assets required to support full litany of cyber security controls both CONUS & OCONUS that improve security posture from vulnerabilities, integrate / ensure adherence to DoW mandated security controls
 for the Naval Enterprise Network (NEN). A significant amount of those assets have reached end-of-life and are no longer supported by the vendors, which potentially makes the infrastructure vulnerable to$$, NULL, $$Exhibit P-40, Budget Line Item Justification: PB 2027 Navy                                                                                                                     Date: April 2026
